COURSES.name: Applications in Biological Engineering
COURSES.description: Overview of the research and applications of biological engineering, such as bioprocessing, biotechnology, transport processes, biosensors, bioremediation, biological materials and biomedicine.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: BSC 2010 or equivalent.

COURSES.name: Land and Water Resources Engineering
COURSES.description: Introduces hydrology, flow through porous media, flood routing, grade control structures and erosion control.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ENV 3040C or CGN 3421 or (COP 2271 and COP 2271L) and MAP 2302.

COURSES.name: Physical and Rheological Properties of Biological Materials
COURSES.description: Theory and use of physical and rheological properties of biological materials in agricultural engineering applications.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: CHM 2045 and MAC 2313 and PHY 2048.

COURSES.name: Fundamentals and Applications of Biosensors
COURSES.description: Provides a broad introduction to the field of biosensors, as well as an in-depth and quantitative view of biosensor design and performance analysis. Fundamental application of biosensor theory will be demonstrated, including: recognition, transduction, signal acquisition, and post processing/data analysis.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAP 2302 and BSC 2010 and CHM 2200.

COURSES.name: Biological Engineering Design 2
COURSES.description: Senior capstone design project.
COURSES.prerequisites: Credits: 2; Prereq: senior standing (4EG), ABE 4042C and two courses in area of specialization.

COURSES.name: Controlled Environment Agriculture Systems Design
COURSES.description: Introduces the engineering design of controlled-environment agriculture systems, including glazing materials selection, fan-sizing for mechanical ventilation, lighting distribution, cooling system design with fan-and-pad evaporative cooling, and heating system design with hot water floor heating.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAC 1147 and 3 credits of physics.

COURSES.name: Post-Harvest Operations Engineering
COURSES.description: Engineering principles and practices of post-harvest operations for the maintenance of quality of agricultural products. Design of systems and facilities.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ABE 3612C.

COURSES.name: Special Topics: App Life Cycle Assessmnt in BE
COURSES.description: Variable subjects provide content for the study of agricultural engineering topics not offered in other courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: instructor permission.

COURSES.name: Special Topics: Environmental Biotechnology
COURSES.description: Variable subjects provide content for the study of agricultural engineering topics not offered in other courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: instructor permission.

COURSES.name: Special Topics: Food Waste & the Circular Bioe
COURSES.description: Variable subjects provide content for the study of agricultural engineering topics not offered in other courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: instructor permission.

COURSES.name: Special Topics: Advanced Robotic Systems Desig
COURSES.description: Variable subjects provide content for the study of agricultural engineering topics not offered in other courses.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: instructor permission.

COURSES.name: Work Experience in Biological Engineering
COURSES.description: Work experience in the biological engineering industry with advisor approval.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Advisor approval

COURSES.name: Recent Developments and Applications in Biosensors
COURSES.description: Introduction to biosensors, design and performance analysis. Fundamental application of biosensor theory will be demonstrated, including recognition, transduction, signal acquisition, and post processing/data analysis.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: At least senior status in engineering and background in biology including biomolecules.

COURSES.name: Advanced Controlled Environment Agriculture Systems Design
COURSES.description: Targets engineering design of controlled environment agriculture systems, including glazing materials selection, fan sizing, lighting distribution, cooling, and heating systems design.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAC 1147 and any three-credit university-level course in physics.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Waste Management
COURSES.description: Engineering analysis and design of systems for the collection, storage, treatment, transport, and utilization of livestock and other agricultural organic wastes and wastewaters. Field trips to operating systems and laboratory evaluation of materials and processes.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: 4 or higher classification.

COURSES.name: Applied Control for Automation and Robots
COURSES.description: Introduction to industrial controls, programmable logic controllers, and manipulator application programming in agricultural and biological engineering. Kinematics, dynamics, and control strategies for serial link manipulators in agricultural applications.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: EML 5311.

COURSES.name: Nanotechnology in Water Research
COURSES.description: Applications of environmental nanotechnology to water quality control. Fate and transport of nanomaterials in hydrologic pathways.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Basic knowledge of hydrology, environmental engineering, and water chemistry.

COURSES.name: Agricultural Decision Systems
COURSES.description: Computerized decision systems for agriculture. Expert systems, decision support systems, simulations, and types of applications in agriculture.

COURSES.name: Advanced Biological Systems Modeling
COURSES.description: This course serves as an advanced graduate class for continued biological modeling and covers topics such as: (1) formulating, solving analytical and numerical problems with programming, (2) dynamic biological models; (3) object-oriented design and agent-based modeling, (4) High Performance Computing and Global Sensitivity and Uncertainty Analysis.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ABE 5643C.

COURSES.name: Seminar
COURSES.description: Preparation and presentation of reports on specialized aspects of research in agricultural engineering and agricultural operations management.

COURSES.name: Applied Mathematics in Engineering and Agriculture
COURSES.description: Mathematical methods, including regression analysis, graphical techniques, and analytical and numerical solution of ordinary and partial differential equations, relevant to engineering in agriculture and the related sciences.

COURSES.name: Advanced Research
COURSES.description: Research for doctoral students before admission to candidacy. Designed for students with a master's degree in the field of study or for students who have been accepted for a doctoral program. Not appropriate for students who have been admitted to candidacy.

COURSES.name: The Qur'an as Literature
COURSES.description: Approaches the Qur'an from a literary standpoint by examining its history, structure, style, major themes, and impact on Arabic literature, Islamic thought, and Muslim culture.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ARA 1131 or ABT 3500 or REL 2000 or REL 2362 or REL 4361 or senior standing.

COURSES.name: Introduction to Financial Accounting
COURSES.description: Conceptual introduction to financial accounting. Emphasis is placed on wealth and income measurement and the preparation and interpretation of conventional financial statements.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Sophomore standing or higher.

sections.note: This class requires online proctoring for exams. You will need a webcam and reliable, high-speed internet access for this course. For lecture recording time and location visit https://warrington.ufl.edu/undergraduate-current-students/video-lectures/

COURSES.name: Introduction to Managerial Accounting
COURSES.description: Accounting for cost reporting and control. Reports, statements and analytical tools used by management.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 2021.

sections.note: This class requires online proctoring for exams. You will need a webcam and reliable, high-speed internet access for this course. For lecture recording time and location visit https://warrington.ufl.edu/undergraduate-current-students/video-lectures/

COURSES.name: Exploring Careers in Accounting
COURSES.description: Introductory overview of accounting as a field of study and the career opportunities available within accounting, in sectors such as public accounting, professional and financial services, industry, government, entrepreneurship, and other.

COURSES.name: Financial Accounting and Reporting 1
COURSES.description: Covers the theoretical structure of financial accounting, required financial statements, revenue recognition, operating assets and current liabilities.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ACG 2021 and ACG 2071 with minimum grades of B) and score of 70% on the Fisher School of Accounting Financial Accounting Competency Assessment and score of 70% on the Fisher School of Accounting Managerial Competency Assessment.

COURSES.name: Business Processes and Accounting Information System
COURSES.description: Examination of the accounting information systems in a business organization. Coverage extends over topics such as business processes, internal controls, and the fundamentals of accounting information systems analysis, design, implementation and control.
COURSES.prerequisites:
Prereq: (ACG 2021 and ACG 2071 with minimum grades of B) and (CGS 2531 or ISM
3013).

COURSES.name: Financial Accounting and Reporting 2
COURSES.description: Continuation of ACG 3101 and includes coverage of accounting for investments, non-current liabilities and equities, accounting for income taxes, derivatives, accounting changes, statement of cash flows and earnings per share.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 3101 with minimum grade of C and FIN 3403.

COURSES.name: Cost and Managerial Accounting
COURSES.description: Extends cost and managerial coverage beyond that covered in ACG 2071. Topics include quantitative cost estimation, standard costing, flexible budgets, inventory management, pricing decisions, balanced scorecard, costs of quality, capital budgeting, transfer pricing and performance evaluations.
COURSES.prerequisites:
Prereq: (ACG 3101 and ACG 3401 with minimum grades of C) and QMB 3250 and (MAC
2234 or MAC 2312).

COURSES.name: Introduction to Auditing
COURSES.description: Introduces the basic concepts, principles and environment of financial statement auditing. The course emphasizes the audit decision-making process, researching audit standards, audit planning, evidence evaluation, audit reports, ethics and legal liability.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 4111 and ACG 4341 with minimum grades of C and AC classification.

COURSES.name: Financial Accounting
COURSES.description: Introduction for prospective managers. Primary emphasis on financial reporting and analysis.

COURSES.name: Managerial Accounting
COURSES.description: Introduction for prospective managers. Primary emphasis on management control systems.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 5005.

COURSES.name: Advanced Accounting
COURSES.description: Reporting of business combinations, equity method of accounting for investments in stocks, and issues concerning consolidated financial statements.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: 7AC Standing; ACG 5647(C) and TAX 5027(C)

COURSES.name: Auditing I
COURSES.description: Concepts and theory underlying the audit of third party assertions. Coverage includes the audit environment, risk assessment, evidential search and evaluation, internal controls, audit programs and audit reporting.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ACG 4111 and ACG 4341 with minimum grades of C, senior standing or higher, accounting major) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management student, Auditing Minor student, and ACG 5075 with minimum grade of C).

sections.note: This class is in Module 3.  Classes meet from January 13  February 28.
This class is in Module 3.  Classes meet from January 13  February 28.

COURSES.name: Auditing II
COURSES.description: Second of a two course sequence. Applies the concepts and theory of auditing to gain assurance about key business processes and financial statement assertions. Coverage includes: audit sampling, revenue process, acquisition process, human resource management process, inventory management, resource management processes; completion activities, audit reports and subsequent events.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (ACG 5637 or ACG 4632 with minimum grades of C, senior standing or higher, accounting major) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management student, Auditing Minor student, ACG 5637 with minimum grade of C).

sections.note: This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.
This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.

COURSES.name: Accounting Regulation
COURSES.description: Private and public sector accounting institutions and their respective professional literature. Research techniques for addressing accounting issues emphasized through case assignments.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 5647 (C) and Class GE 7AC.

sections.note: This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.

COURSES.name: Accounting for Income Taxes
COURSES.description: In-depth study of the financial reporting standards for the effects of income taxes on a corporation's operating results and financial position.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: TAX 5065 with a minimum grade of C. Graduate accounting students only

sections.note: This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.

COURSES.name: Accounting Theory
COURSES.description: Theoretical frameworks essential to explore structure, features, and limitations of accounting and financial reporting.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 5815, 7AC standing.

sections.note: This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.
This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.

COURSES.name: Forensic Accounting
COURSES.description: Analysis of contemporary forensic and investigative accounting. Topics include: fraud auditing, litigation support, valuation, cyber-crime, and other key forensic topics.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: (Master of Accounting Student, ACG 5647 and ACG 5226 with minimum grades of C) OR (Master of Science in Information Systems and Operations Management Student, Auditing Minor student, ACG 5647 with minimum grade of C).

sections.note: This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.
This class is in Module 4.  Classes meet from March 3  April 25.

COURSES.name: International Auditing
COURSES.description: Global perspective of auditing issues including international auditing standards and corporate governance practices providing an in depth analysis of the audit of multinational companies, cross border transactions and transfer pricing within affiliated groups of companies.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 5647  (C) , ACG 5226 , Class GE 7, and College EQ AC

sections.note: This class is in Module 3.  Classes meet from January 13  February 28.

COURSES.name: Data Analytics for Accounting
COURSES.description: Application of data analytics techniques to accounting information. It explores how vast amounts of data and programming tools change how management uses data to attain organizational goals, obtain relevant information from public sources, identify the value of innovative ways to apply data to measure firm performance and develop models to gain knowledge from such datasets using machine learning.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ACG 5226 and Master of Accounting student.

sections.note: This class is in Module 3.  Classes meet from January 3  February 28
This class is in Module 3.  Classes meet from January 13  February 28.

COURSES.name: Data Analysis Skills
COURSES.description: In this course the students are introduced to archival research. The primary focus is on introducing the most commonly used datasets on WRDS (Compustat, CRSP and IBES) and learning SAS to manage and analyze these datasets.

This is a Mod 3 section. Details: https://warrington.ufl.edu/graduate-current-students/academic-calendar/

COURSES.name: Advertising Strategy
COURSES.description: Overview of the strategic planning process required to develop a successful strategic, persuasive communication plan such as an advertising, integrated marketing communications, or social marketing campaign. Case studies and projects teach the skills needed to address a variety of communications management issues and engage audiences in diverse marketplaces.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAR 3023 and ADV 3008 with minimum grades of C and ADV major.

COURSES.name: Principles of Advertising
COURSES.description: Overview of the concepts, strategies, and tactics of modern advertising. Explores the role of advertising in society, culture, and economics, as well as the industry and its key organizations. Introduces specific practices used to develop, place, and evaluate both traditional and digital ads.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: Sophomore standing or higher.

COURSES.name: Digital Media Sales
COURSES.description: Provides a solid understanding of digital media sales and the digital environment. Student will be able to identify & explain key concepts related to sales efforts in digital and social media, implement digital and social media sales efforts, and justify integrated efforts with research, measurements and trends.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 and MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C.

COURSES.name: Artificial Intelligence and Advertising
COURSES.description: Provides a comprehensive understanding of AI and its impact on the advertising industry. Explore a range of AI-driven tools, techniques, and technologies while examining their practical applications in marketing and advertising campaigns. Additionally, covers the ethical and societal implications of AI technology in human communication and marketing.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: ADV 3008 & MAR 3023 with minimum grades of C & Advertising major.

COURSES.name: Branding
COURSES.description: Principles of branding and brand strategy; learn to think creatively and critically about strategies and tactics applied to build and manage brands with insight into diverse audiences.
COURSES.prerequisites: Prereq: MAR 3023 and ADV 3008 with minimum grades of C.
